@Node "Purpose" "Purpose of IdentD"

Extract from @{"RFC 1413" link "rfc1413/Main"}:
The Identification Protocol (a.k.a., "ident", a.k.a., "the Ident Protocol")
provides a means to determine the identity of a user of a particular TCP
connection. Given a TCP port number pair, it returns a character string
which identifies the owner of that connection on the server's system.

IdentD is a daemon for AmiTCP/IP 4.x which answers identification requests
defined in this RFC. With this server installed you will get rid of this
ugly "~" in front of your login name on IRC or get into priviliged FTP
access classes on some FTP servers.

If you prefer anonymity and don't want to relevate your login name this way
you should not install IdentD.
@EndNode

@Node "Features" "Features of IdentD"

Features of IdentD are:

- @{"RFC 1413" link "rfc1413/Main"} compliant

- works with AmiTCP/IP 4.x

- timeout for hanging connections

- uses operating system names defined in RFC 1700

- no dummy: it will really check wether a connection exists

- authentication can be disabled for certain users
@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "Installation of IdentD"

These steps are required to install IdentD:

1.) Copy the binary "serv/identd" to "AmiTCP:serv/identd".

2.) Add the contents of "db/inetd.conf.add" to "AmiTCP:db/inetd.conf".

3.) If you use AmiTCP/IP 4.0 Demo you have to restart AmiTCP/IP.

If you want to disable authentication for an user create a file called
".noident" in his home directory.
@EndNode

@Node "Trouble" "Troube Shooting"

There are several reasons why authentication may fail:

1.) You made an error during the installation.

    You can check the correct installation with this command:

    @{b}telnet localhost auth@{ub}

    AmiTCP/IP's response should look like this:

    @{b}AmiTCP/IP_telnet 4.1 (6.8.94) 
    Trying localhost ...
    Connected to localhost.@{ub}

    Now enter this:

    @{b}4,2@{ub}

    You should get this response:

    @{b}4, 2 : ERROR : NO-USER
    Connection closed by foreign host.@{ub}

2.) Wrong login name

    IdentD returns the name of AmiTCP/IP's current user. So if you are
    logged in as "root" but use an IRC client as "joe" identifaction will
    fail of course.

3.) Multiple IP addresses

    Some hosts have multiple IP addresses ("ftp.uni-paderborn.de" e.g. has
    two IP addresses for Ethernet and one for FDDI). If you connect to such
    a host it might happen that the host uses another IP address for the
    identifaction request than your host uses for the TCP connection. In
    this case IdentD will not be able to find the connection and respond
    with an NO-USER error. As a result the authentication will fail.

    The only way to avoid this problem is to try all addresses until the
    authentication is successful. But due to dynamic routing the "right"
    IP address might change.
@EndNode

@Node "History" "History of IdentD"

1.0:
- first public release

1.1:
- fixed wrong error message on query for non existing connection

1.2:
- improved timeout handling
- removed some errors in the documentation
@EndNode

